Port to Linux 6.18 investigation: this library bundles its own copy of the
kernel's nfnetlink_conntrack.h enum rather than the real uapi header.
Upstream Linux added CTA_TIMESTAMP_EVENT to that enum, between
CTA_STATUS_MASK and __CTA_MAX, at some point after this library's bundled
snapshot was taken but before 6.18 -- so the running 6.18 kernel's real
enum has it, but this library's copy doesn't.

Since 100-add-ask-runtime-state-attrs.patch inserts
CTA_LAYERSCAPE_FP_ORIG/CTA_LAYERSCAPE_FP_REPLY right after
CTA_STATUS_MASK in both the kernel and this library, the missing entry
here shifts every enum value after it by one relative to the kernel's
real numbering. Netlink attribute types are wire integers, so this
isn't cosmetic: the kernel tags FP_ORIG data with one integer, this
library reads it back under the wrong slot (actually CTA_TIMESTAMP_EVENT
data, or nothing), FP_ORIG's real data gets misfiled as FP_REPLY, and the
kernel's real FP_REPLY attribute lands one past this library's CTA_MAX
and gets dropped by validation. End result: CMM never receives valid
interface/mark metadata for any connection (visible as "orig-ifindex:
-(0)" etc. in `cmm -c 'show connections'` for every entry, even under
real sustained traffic), so it can never install a hardware fast-path
route no matter how healthy FMan/PCD is.

Add the missing enum entry in the same position the kernel has it so
the numeric attribute types line up again.

--- a/include/libnetfilter_conntrack/linux_nfnetlink_conntrack.h
+++ b/include/libnetfilter_conntrack/linux_nfnetlink_conntrack.h
@@ -60,6 +60,7 @@
 	CTA_SYNPROXY,
 	CTA_FILTER,
 	CTA_STATUS_MASK,
+	CTA_TIMESTAMP_EVENT,
 	CTA_LAYERSCAPE_FP_ORIG,
 	CTA_LAYERSCAPE_FP_REPLY,
 	__CTA_MAX
